			<h4>
				<div>
					&ldquo;Can do absolutely anything he likes with a keyboard&rdquo;<br>&thinsp;&mdash;&thinsp;Chicago Tribune 
				</div>
			</h4>
			<p>
				Since his debut at age 16 with the Los Angeles Philharmonic and Esa-Pekka Salonen, Andrew von Oeyen has established himself as one of the most captivating pianists of his generation. 
			</p>
			<p>
				This is von Oeyen&rsquo;s first time performing in Winnipeg, though his reputation surely precedes him. His star is rising fast, for he is an artist of a special breed: a dashing, magnetic performer and a consummate technician who woos general audiences and the exacting critics of the classical music world equally. 
			</p>
			<p>
				The LA Times writes that von Oeyen boasts &ldquo;indisputable gifts [and] an extravagantly thorough and effortless technique.&rdquo; The Chicago Tribune goes even further: &ldquo;Brilliant technique can be taken for granted among today&rsquo;s concert pianists. But von Oeyen&rsquo;s playing&thinsp;&hellip;&thinsp;leaves you convinced that he can do absolutely anything he likes with a keyboard.&rdquo; 
			</p>
			<p>
				This concert will see von Oeyen exploring somewhat iconoclastic territory. He&rsquo;ll perform Shostakovich&rsquo;s playful Piano Concerto No. 1. Rich with humour and folk elements, it stands in contrast to the more pensive Shostakovich work performed by the MCO in October. 
			</p>
			<p>
				Composer Christos Hatzis is a Canadian treasure, and the MCO is only too pleased to again perform Zeitgeist (Spirit of the Age). Much like von Oeyen, Hatsiz has captured the hearts of audiences and critics alike with his eclectic repertoire, which is at once traditionalist and adventurous. 
			</p>
			<p>
				The concert goes out with a bang, wrapping up with Mozart&rsquo;s 29th symphony, a landmark work that shows the 18 year-old composer really coming into his own. 
			</p>
